abstract: Over the years, one building in Palo Alto, Calif., has been home to some of Silicon Valley’s most successful start-ups.
snippet: Over the years, one building in Palo Alto, Calif., has been home to some of Silicon Valley’s most successful start-ups.
lead_paragraph: PALO ALTO, Calif., Sept. 13 — The building at 165 University Avenue here has been so good to the Amidi family that Saeed Amidi says it is blessed with good karma. There are some high-technology entrepreneurs who would agree.

headline.main: Rental Building’s Good Karma Nurtures Success
headline.print_headline: Rental Building’s Good Karma Nurtures Silicon Valley Success

abstract: The group whose $10 million prize spurred privately financed rocketeers to send a small piloted craft to the cusp of space in 2004 has issued a new challenge: an unmanned moon shot. With the audacious new contest comes a much bigger prize: up to $25 million, paid for by Google, the ubiquitous Internet company.

abstract: Google’s new page about the Australian election shows a new approach to publishing: a mix of human- and machine-selected information.
snippet: Google’s new page about the Australian election shows a new approach to publishing: a mix of human- and machine-selected information.
lead_paragraph: We should be past the debate of a few years ago about whether Google wants to be a “portal”—in the sense that Yahoo and AOL offer sections after sections about various topics. After all, for many sites Google is an even bigger front door than their own home pages.

headline.main: Google as Portal, With a Twist
